---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "capabilities")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        "AI assistant" undersells it. With the four Claude products you can produce
        <strong>documents, scripts, web pages, prototypes, deployed apps, and end-to-end automations</strong> —
        without leaving a chat box for most of them.
      </p>
      <p>This lesson is the map. Pick the row that fits what you want to make.</p>

      <h2>Things you can ship today, in a single chat</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>Where:</strong> claude.ai</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <li><strong>Writing.</strong> Briefs, emails, ad copy, blog posts, speeches, eulogies, contracts (drafts).</li>
          <li><strong>Analysis.</strong> Paste a spreadsheet or PDF and ask for trends, summaries, anomalies.</li>
          <li><strong>Planning.</strong> Trip itineraries, project plans, meeting agendas, budgets.</li>
          <li><strong>Learning aids.</strong> Flashcards, study guides, lecture summaries, practice problems.</li>
          <li><strong>One-page apps.</strong> A unit converter, a tip calculator, a personality quiz — runs inside an artifact.</li>
          <li><strong>Diagrams.</strong> Flowcharts, sequence diagrams, mind maps — exported as images or Mermaid.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Things you can build this week</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>Where:</strong> Claude Code (terminal) or Claude Design (visual)</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <li><strong>A personal CLI.</strong> "Summarize my open browser tabs", "rename these photos by date".</li>
          <li><strong>A small website.</strong> Portfolio, landing page, event RSVP, small game, family blog.</li>
          <li><strong>A Chrome extension.</strong> Replace boring buttons, add a "summarize this page" command.</li>
          <li><strong>A bot.</strong> Slack, Discord, Telegram — answers questions, posts daily summaries.</li>
          <li><strong>Internal tools.</strong> A dashboard pulling data from a Google Sheet, a form that emails the team.</li>
          <li><strong>Data pipelines.</strong> "Read this CSV, clean these columns, save as Parquet, plot the result."</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Things teams ship in production</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>Where:</strong> Claude API, often coordinated through Claude Code or Cowork</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <li><strong>Customer-facing apps</strong> with Claude as the brain — support, tutoring, writing tools, code review.</li>
          <li><strong>Agent workflows</strong> — Claude reads, decides, calls APIs, writes back results. Think "research bot that emails a digest each morning".</li>
          <li><strong>Document pipelines</strong> — invoices, contracts, medical records: parsed, classified, summarized at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Embedded copilots</strong> inside existing products — a "help me write this" button next to any text field.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>The capability cheat-sheet</h2>
      <p>What can Claude read and produce? Almost any text-shaped thing, plus some non-text:</p>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.6rem 0;">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background: var(--surface-2);">
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Input</th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Output</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Plain text, prose, instructions</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Plain text, prose, structured replies</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Source code in any language</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Source code, patches, explanations, tests</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">PDFs, Word docs, slides</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Summaries, rewrites, extractions</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Images (photos, screenshots, charts)</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Descriptions, transcriptions, classifications</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">CSVs, JSON, tables</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Cleaned data, analysis, charts</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Whole codebases (Claude Code)</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Edits, refactors, new features, working apps</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">A sentence describing UI</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.7rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Working HTML/React (Claude Design)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Honest take: which product should I open?</h2>
      <p>
        These products overlap a lot. <strong>Claude Code is the most powerful</strong> — it can do almost
        everything Claude.ai can, plus everything Claude.ai can't (read your files, run your tests, edit
        a real project). For a developer in a project folder, it's the default. Claude.ai's real edge is
        narrower than the marketing suggests:
      </p>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.6rem 0; font-size: 0.92rem;">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background: var(--surface-2);">
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Situation</th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Open</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">In a project folder, touching code</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude Code</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Long-running chores against a repo (and you don't want to babysit)</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude Cowork</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Needs to look like something visual</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude Design</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">On phone / tablet / someone else's laptop</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Need to drop in a PDF / image / spreadsheet that isn't in any repo</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">A non-developer (spouse, manager, parent) needs to use it</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Want a persistent "custom assistant" with knowledge files (projects feature)</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Want to share a chat link with someone</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">No paid plan yet</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude.ai</strong> (free tier)</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Embedding Claude into your own product</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Claude API</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Want a background daemon with persistent memory</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><strong>Hermes / OpenClaw</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        Phrased differently: if you have a terminal open in the right folder, you'll usually reach for Claude Code.
        The other products exist for the cases where you <em>don't</em> — or where the work isn't about code at all.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Permission to start small.</strong> Most useful tools are tiny — a 30-line script, a one-page site,
        a Claude.ai project with a good system prompt. You don't need a grand vision. You need one thing
        you'd find slightly annoying to do by hand.
      </div>

      <h2>Where to find prompts you can just copy</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/cookbook">Cookbook</a> page has copy-paste starter prompts organized by goal —
      writing, coding, web, automation, design. When you finish the tour, that's your launchpad.</p>

      <Reveal q="Do I need a paid plan?">
        Most of what's in "today" works on a free Claude.ai account. Heavy use, very long files, and Claude Code
        usage tend to lead people to a paid plan. Start free; upgrade when you hit a limit you care about.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="What can Claude not do?">
        Real-time anything (live trading, current sports scores) unless you give it tools to fetch. It also
        can't take physical actions or sign legal documents. And it should not be the only check on
        anything safety-critical — medical, legal, financial decisions need a human in the loop.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
